deck_name: The Inner Ojamachinations of My Mind
deck_description:
This is the Dinosaur Runick Prediction Princess list that features Summoner of Illusions that can be found in Part 1 of my Summoner of Illusions Prediction Princess Guide, or at least that was what it was supposed to be. In my Honorable Mentions list of monsters for SoI, I mentioned that Ojama King and Ojama Knight, blocking off up to 3 and up to 2 of your opponent's unused Main Monster Zones, respectively, doesn't actually do anything since your opponent could theoretically still play around a few of the MMZs being locked if they had a way to deal with the other threat your board presented, Deus-X Krawler. And while this list was supposed to be the Dinosaur Runick Prediction Princess list, I had a revelation on how to use both Ojama King and Knight, and decided to explain my Dino Runick PPrincess list while also showing off this incredibly gimmicky gameplan this Deck has that revolves around either Ojama King or Ojama Knight and the card I completely forgot came out: Gorgon of Zilofthonia. 

Gorgon of Zilofthonia is a LINK-3 monster with all 3 of its Link Arrows pointing upwards (Up, Upper-Left, Upper-Right). Neither player can Summon/Set monsters to the zones that it points to and monsters it points to cannot attack and have their effects negated. Essentially, Zilofthonia will basically renders 3 of your opponent's Main Monster Zones that it points to unusable as they cannot Summon/Set monsters to those Zones. If you pair that up with either Ojama King or Ojama Knight and block the other Main Monster Zones that Zilofthonia does not point to, you have basically created a terrible way of locking up all 5 of your opponent's Main Monster Zones, for the turn since the Ojama will be destroyed during the End Phase due to being Special Summoned off of SoI. It's really gimmicky and loses to any piece of removal or any piece of negation, but innovation stops for no one, despite how bad some of those ideas may be.

Full combo is any way to get to Ib the World Chalice Justiciar and any Runick Quick-Play Spell. In this Deck, that would be Souleating Oviraptor and any Runick Quick-Play Spell like Runick Tip. Normal Summon Oviraptor and activate its effect to add Jurrac Megalo from Deck to hand. Activate Megalo in hand to Special Summon it because you control a Dinosaur monster. Synchro Megalo and Oviraptor into Ib the World Chalice Justiciar. On Synchro Summon, Ib adds World Legacy Monstrosity from Deck to hand. Activate Tip to Special Summon Sleipnir the Runick Mane to the EMZ. Activate Monstrosity targeting Sleipnir to Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and Pot of the Forbidden from Deck. Xyz Sleipnir and Pot into Mereologic Aggregator who sends Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY on Xyz Summon. Herald triggers in GY to add Prediction Princess Tarotrei from Deck to hand. Activate Aggregator's other effect, targeting Herald in GY, detaching 1 material, and attaching Herald from GY. Link Aggregator and Ib into I:P Masquerena. Herald triggers as it is sent to GY again and searches for Underworld Ritual of Prediction. Activate Underworld Ritual to Ritual Summon Tarotrei by tributing Bibliomuse. Bibliomuse triggers off of being tributed and Special Summons herself back from GY face-down. Tarotrei activates to flip Bibliomuse face-up, and then Bibliomuse's Flip Effect activates to add Prediction Princess Tarotreith and another Underworld Ritual from Deck to hand. Activate Underworld Ritual to Ritual Summon Tarotreith face-down by tributing Bibliomuse. During the End Phase, Tarotrei activates to Special Summon Pot from GY face-down. During your opponent's Standby Phase, banish Underworld Ritual from GY to Special Summon Bibliomuse from Deck face-down and activate Tarotrei's effect to flip Tarotreith face-up. Tarotreith's Flip Effect activates to Special Summon Summoner of Illusions from Deck face-down. On a new Chain, Tarotreith's other effect can be used to flip Bibliomuse, Pot, and SoI face-up. Bibliomuse's Flip Effect searches for a Prediction Princess monster and a Ritual Spell from Deck for follow-up while giving your Ritual Monsters targeting and destruction protection from your opponent's card effects. Pot's Flip Effect activates which allows you to look at your opponent's hand and shuffle a card from it back into their Deck. Try to get rid of something that can either destroy or negate your cards. And SoI can Tribute your spent Tarotreith to Special Summon Ojama King from Extra Deck. When Ojama King hits the field, it allows you to block off 3 of your opponent's unused MMZs. Block 3 of them off starting from the far left or far right, moving in. During your opponent's Main Phase, I:P can perform a Link Summon using itself and your spent Tarotrei to Link Summon Gorgon of Zilofthonia into the correct EMZ so that Zilofthonia points to the MMZs that Ojama King didn't block off. Now, your opponent basically cannot use their MMZs and hopefully Pot got rid of the card in your opponent's hand that can break the lock. 

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Pot of the Forbidden which has a Flip Effect that lets you choose between Drawing 2 cards, returning all Spell/Traps on the field to the hand, destroying all monsters your opponent controls, or looking at your opponent's hand and shuffling a card from it back into the Deck. 1 Summoner of Illusions whose Flip Effect is a mandatory effect activation when it is flipped face-up which tributes another monster you control to Special Summon a Fusion Monster from your Extra Deck, but that monster is destroyed during the End Phase of this turn. For the dinosaur engine, we are playing 1 Miscellaneousaurus, 3 Souleating Oviraptor, and 1 Jurrac Megalo. I think I actually prefer this Dinosaur engine over the Draconnet engine from my last Runick Prediction Princess list. I just think that these dino cards make getting to Ib the World Chalice Justiciar a whole lot easier and much more flexible than what Draconnet and a Level 2 Normal Tuner can provide. Misc can Quick Effect send itself from hand to GY during the Main Phase to make your Dinosaur monsters unaffected by your opponent's activated effects during this Main Phase. And, you can banish it from GY along with any other number of Dinosaurs from your GY to Special Summon a Dinosaur from Deck with a Level equal to the total number of monsters you banished, but it is destroyed during the End Phase. Oviraptor takes a Dinosaur monster from your Deck and either adds it to hand or sends it to GY on Normal or Special Summon. That's pretty much all that we are using it for, but just like in the combo I described earlier, Oviraptor just makes Ib on its own through searching for Megalo. Speaking of, we are pretty much only using Megalo for its effect in hand which allows you to Special Summon it if you control a Dinosaur monster. Megalo, being the Tuner in this engine to make Ib, is already a whole lot more flexible than a Level 2 vanilla Tuner when you are playing Draconnet. Sure, if you draw just Megalo and a Runick Spell or just the Level 2 vanilla Tuner and a Runick Spell, you can Normal Summon them and use the Runick Spell for either the Level 4 Geri the Runick Fangs or the Level 3 Munin the Runick Wings, and then make Ib from there. That's fine and all, but Megalo can still Special Summon itself from your hand if you control a Dinosaur monster. You could argue that Draconnet can Summon the Level 2 vanilla tuner from hand, but if Draconnet gets negated, you've just spent your Normal Summon on Draconnet, have no way to get the tuner on field to make Ib, and are pretty much a sitting duck. However, if you open Ovi and Megalo, you can try to bait out interaction by Normal Summoning Ovi and attempting to use its effect to search for Misc or even another copy of itself because it can. And if that is stopped, you can just Special Summon Megalo from hand. Not to mention that if you draw Ovi and Misc and your stupid brain did not activate Misc before Normal Summoning Ovi, you can still activate Misc in hand, send it to GY, and then banish itself from GY to Special Summon the Level 1 Megalo from Deck. You can also search Megalo off of Fossil Dig as well, unlike the vanilla tuners you are playing for Draconnet. None of them are Cyberse monsters, so you can't even use Cynet Mining to theoretically search for them. I don't know why you would search for a vanilla, but I am just trying to say that Fossil Dig can search for Megalo which can then Special Summon itself.

For Spell/Traps: 3 Fossil Dig which searches for a Level 6 or lower Dinosaur monster from Deck. This card is not a once per turn and it doesn't require sending a card from hand to GY as cost like Cynet Mining does. Runick Prediction Princess actually does care for maintaining resources in hand, so not having to go neg-1 to search for your starter is a pretty big upside to this Dinosaur engine. Not a once per turn either which is also a huge upgrade over Mining, but that's probably pretty obvious. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 1 Runick Fountain which allows us to activate Runick Quick-Play Spells from our hand during your opponent’s turn and if you activate a Runick Quick-Play Spell Card, you can target up to 3 Runick Quick-Play Spells in your GY and place them on the bottom of your Deck in any order and draw the same number of cards. For the Runick Quick-Play Spells: 3 Runick Tip, 3 Runick Slumber, 1 Runick Freezing Curses, 3 Runick Destruction, 1 Runick Flashing FIre, 1 Runick Dispelling, and 1 Runick Smiting Storm. Each of them allows you to choose between an effect that is unique to the card and an effect that Special Summons a Runick monster from your Extra Deck to the EMZ, but you are forced to skip your next Battle Phase. Tip searches for a Runick card from Deck before banishing the top card of your opponent’s Deck. Slumber targets a face-up monster on the field and prevents it from being destroyed by battle or card effect the next instance it would be this turn, but it cannot attack and then you banish the top 3 cards of your opponent’s Deck. Freezing Curses targets and negate the effects of an Effect Monster your opponent controls until the end of the turn and banishes the top 3 cards of their Deck. Destruction targets and destroys a Spell/Trap your opponent controls and then banishes the top 4 cards of their Deck. Flashing Fire targets and destroys a Special Summoned monster your opponent controls before banishing the top 2 cards of your opponent’s Deck. Dispelling, if your opponent adds a card(s) from their Deck to their hand, discards a random card out of their hand and then banishes the top 2 cards of their Deck. Smiting Storm banishes cards from the top of your opponent’s Deck up to the number of cards they control. 2 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. 1 Called by the Grave and 1 Triple Tactics Talent. Finally, 2 World Legacy Pawns which allows you to target a face-down monster you control and then changes it to face-up Attack or Defense Position.

Extra Deck: 1 Sleipnir, the Runick Mane as our Level 9 monster to get off of a Runick Quick-Play Spell. 1 Ojama King which chooses up to 3 of your opponent's unused MMZs and prevents them from being used while it's on field. This effect is applied once Ojama King hits the field or when it becomes face-up on the field to not confuse you on how it activates. You could play Ojama Knight instead, but Ojama King has a 3000 DEF stat whereas Knight only has 2500 DEF. You could technically also play other Fusion Monsters for SoI as well. 1 Geri, the Runic Fangs which is just a Level 4 we can grab off of a Runick Quick-Play Spell to Synchro with Jurrac Megalo into Ib. 1 Hugin, the Runick Wings which adds a Runick Field Spell from your Deck to your hand on Special Summon and if another card(s) you control would be destroyed by card effect, you can banish her from field instead. She is also another good Summon off of SoI if we weren't trying to be goofy with this Deck. 1 Wind Pegasus @Ignister just to help clear a Hugin from your EMZ when Synchroed with Ib, and it also, when another card(s) you control is destroyed by battle or an opponent’s card effect, banish itself from GY to target a card your opponent controls and shuffle it into the Deck. 1 Ib the World Chalice Justiciar which searches for a World Legacy card on Synchro Summon. 1 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from your Deck to your hand if it is sent to the GY. 1 Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Gorgon of Zilofthonia which I already explained, but it also gains ATK equal to the combined original ATK of the monsters it points to and it cannot be destroyed by battle or monster effects while it points to no monsters. 1 S:P Little Knight and 1 I:P Masquerena.

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Mulcharmy Fuwalos, 2 Mulcharmy Purulia, 2 Lightning Storm, 2 Dark Ruler No More, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: There's no place I'd rather be than home!
deck_description:
It's a fun deck to play in the Theme Chronicle event. The small psychic Kozmos special summon the big machine ships from your hand. Kozmo Tincan is your main searcher for the big ships. Kozmo Farmgirl can surprise OTK your opponent if she gets a direct attack. Kozmo Dark Destroyer is your main ship to pilot because it can easily break boards with its targeted destruction effect and big attack stat.

The TCG's Psychic Support

The following cards were initially released in the TCG's Phantom Knightmare (PHNI) set, but now they've found a home in Master Duel!

Psychic Processor is a great card whose main effect allows you to special summon up to 2 Kozmo monsters from your hand and enables the monsters that were special summoned by this effect to attack directly for the rest of the turn. I've stolen quite a few games by using this effect to attack directly with Kozmo Dark Destroyer.

Psychic Arsenal is a decent consistency booster for decks that run low-level psychic monsters and high-level machines. These requirements make it a natural fit for Kozmo decks. Its first effect allows you to target a psychic monster you control and pay 200 life points times its level, then add a machine monster with the same attribute, but a higher level from your deck to your hand. Target a light psychic Kozmo to add Kozmo Sliprider or Kozmo Forerunner to your hand. Target a dark psychic Kozmo or Psychic Processor to add Kozmo Dark Destroyer, Kozmo DOG Fighter, or Kozmo Dark Eclipser to your hand. Psychic Arsenal's second effect allows you to banish it from your graveyard to add 1 of each of your banished psychic and machine monsters to your hand and to the bottom of your deck. It's another decent effect that helps you recover during long grind games.

deck_excerpt: A combo deck based on Chain Material.
deck_description:
A combo deck based on Chain Material. The idea is to spam out several HERO Fusions and then Xyz Summon with them, or fuse using Fusion Gate's effect instead of Chain Material's effect, so you don't get hit with the End Phase destruction effect of Chain Material.

One of the cooler cards you could run for a deck like this is Coach King Giantrainer, but that requires playing a later format/card pool. It combos really well with Chain Material since you need to get rid of your Level 8 Fusions anyways and Chain Material already prevents you from attacking that turn. I definitely recommend running 3 Chain Material in a deck that uses Giantrainer so you're able to summon it more consistently.

This deck is one I used to play a lot back in the Dueling Network days. It's not particularly good, but it's pretty fun!

Uses the March 2012 ban list.

deck_excerpt: A combo deck based on Chain Material.
deck_description: A combo deck based on Chain Material. The idea is to spam out several HERO Fusions and then Xyz Summon with them, or fuse using Fusion Gate's effect instead of Chain Material's effect, so you don't get hit with the End Phase destruction effect of Chain Material.
For TCG Tournaments

At YCS Vancouver I was able to secure a Top 64 finish with Temple of the Kings, a deck that I believe is heavily underestimated in the current format. Despite being left out of most tier lists, the deck has proven itself at both locals and larger events, consistently putting up strong results and catching meta players off guard. What makes the deck powerful is its ability to grind through games by looping Apopus traps, specifically Aous the Serpent and Swamp Deity, which provide a constant stream of omni-negates. On top of that, cards like Verdict of Anubis and Statue of Anguish Pattern give the deck additional win conditions, allowing it to close games in unexpected ways.

The main deck is built to maximize consistency and flexibility. Anubis, the Last Judge and Man with the Mark act as reliable one-card starters, while the Apopus ratio of two Serpent and three Swamp Deity ensures access to the core loop without overcommitting to bricks. Verdict of Anubis, while technically situational, has stolen games outright, making it a worthwhile inclusion. Treasure of the Kings, supported by Terraforming, is the best opener in the deck and can play around Droll effectively. I also chose to incorporate the Kashira package—Unicorn, Fenrir, Birth, and Pressure Planet—which performed extremely well by disrupting opponents early, especially with Unicorn ripping key extra deck pieces.

Rather than relying heavily on hand traps, the deck leans into board breakers to deal with the meta. Super Polymerization, Eclipse, and Droplet are all included to dismantle boards proactively while recycling traps in the process. The only hand trap I ran was Droll, which remains too impactful to ignore, particularly against strategies like Yummy and Vanquish Soul. This balance between proactive disruption and recursive grind power is what makes the deck so resilient.

The extra deck is designed to support both the Apopus engine and the board-breaking approach. Cards like Ty-phon pair well with Treasure of the Kings, while Selene and Accesscode provide a reliable finishing route after a grindy game, even allowing wins through Nibiru. Super Poly targets and niche tech like Secretarian Dragon round out the lineup, ensuring answers to a wide range of threats. The side deck, meanwhile, shifts depending on whether I’m going first or second: Mind Drain and Soul Drain are devastating when going first, while cards like Raigeki, Eclipse, and Spooky Dogwood shine when playing second.

Overall, Temple of the Kings is not just a gimmick deck but a serious contender. Its recursive trap loops generate consistent advantage, and its side deck adaptability lets it handle diverse matchups. Many opponents underestimate it, but once the Apopus engine gets going, the deck feels almost unfair, recycling omni-negates and punishing overextension. My performance at YCS Vancouver is proof of its potential, and I believe the deck deserves far more recognition as a legitimate rogue strategy capable of competing with the top tiers.

deck_excerpt: Machina Trains is actually relevant and powerful in Theme Chronicle's low power metagame!
deck_description:
The power level of nearly every deck is weakened due to Theme Chronicles banlist, and it's time for rogue archetypes to come out of the woodwork and finally shine! 

One of these rogue archetypes include Machina, which summons powerful machines from the GY and Banishment with a compact but powerful resource loop to ensure the pilot is always ahead of the opponent. Machina Citadel, is the ace card of the strategy since it is a quick effect board wipe of all your opponent’s monsters. Machina Overdrive enables a circular resource loop between the banished pile, GY, deck and hand, while Machina Redeployment greatly increased the consistency of the deck. Unclaspare (R4NK enabler, free special summon and foolish burial) and Ruinforce (4600ATK beatstick and banish recursion) have also greatly increased the power for this archetype.

These characteristics enable these machines to compete with Theme Chronicle's meta heavyweights like Sky Striker and Six Samurai.

Control the game, simplify the game-state, then OTK your opponent in one fell swoop with your high ATK Machina Train army!

GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: Hey, wanna listen to some tunes?
deck_description:
Naturia Rosewhip is a tuner floodgate that prevents your opponent from playing more than 1 spell or trap per turn. Killer Tune Cue can special summon Naturia Rosewhip from your hand, deck, or graveyard and Killer Tune Remix can special summon Naturia Rosewhip from your graveyard. Another good tuner this deck can play is Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit because her destruction effect can be activated while she's face-up the field. Also, Naturia Rosewhip and Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit are level 3 tuners, so they can be used as synchro material to summon most of the Killer Tune synchro monsters.

Juke Joint "Killer Tune" and Synchro Overtake are this deck's extenders. Juke Joint gives you an extra normal summon for a tuner monster and can tribute a tuner monster to search for or special summon a Killer Tune monster from your deck. Synchro Overtake can reveal Killer Tune Red Seal or Killer Tune Remix in your extra deck to add or special summon Killer Tune Reco (reveal Red Seal) or Killer Tune Mix (reveal Remix) from your deck or graveyard.

Lastly, Sales Ban, Called by the Grave, and Crossout Designator help deal with this deck's severe weakness to Droll & Lock Bird and Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit.

deck_name: World Chalice Prediction Princess ft. Summoner of Illusions
deck_description:
This is the World Chalice Prediction Princess Deck that features Summoner of Illusions found in part 2 of my Summoner of Illusions Prediction Princess Guide. If you want to play this Deck, I would really recommend cutting the Summoner of Illusions stuff as that is just extra weight on the Deck. I would recommend cutting SoI for Enneacraft Astay.PIXIEA, Prima Materiactor for any non-Pendulum Normal Summonable Normal Monster with 0 ATK, World Legacy Pawns for World Legacy Awakens (if you want), and Flowering Etoile the Melodious Magnificat and Odd-Eyes Vortex Dragon for Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys and something like Infinitrack Earth Slicer or even K9 - EX “Werewolf”. 

I know that a lot of people do not want to see World Chalice because it is just a solitaire Deck that ends on less than nothing now that Apollousa is banned. However, I think it is still a fun Deck to experiment with Prediction Princess since World Chalice is literally the archetype that Ib the World Chalice Justiciar belongs to. My previous list for World Chalice Prediction Princess that aimed to utilize either World Chalice Guardragon Almarduke or First of the Dragons as its Level 9 of choice to target with World Legacy Monstrosity still pretty much stands with the only major difference being that Ib was unbanned since then. Sure, there are also a lot of new additions that the Deck can utilize, such as Miracle Raven to transition from Diviner of the Herald into Lee the World Chalice Fairy, but this version of World Chalice Prediction Princess is much more dumbed down into something that is more digestible for most people. Specifically, it gets rid of Lee which surprisingly simplifies the combo down to any Normal Summonable Normal Monster + World Legacy - “World Chalice”. 

Let’s say that you open Prima Materiactor and World Legacy - “World Chalice”. Normal Summon Prima and Link it off into Imduk the World Chalice Dragon. Use Imduk’s extra Normal Summon for a World Chalice monster to Tribute Summon World Chalice by tributing Imduk. Then, Link World Chalice off into Salamangreat Almiraj. World Chalice triggers in GY because it left the field after being Normal Summoned which allows you to Special Summon Beckoned by the World Chalice and World Chalice Guardragon from your Deck. Beckoned can be treated as a Tuner when used for the Synchro Summon of Ib the World Chalice Justiciar, so Beckoned and Guardragon to GY as Synchro Material to Synchro Summon Ib. On Synchro Summon, Ib searches for World Legacy Monstrosity from Deck. Activate World Chalice Guardragon’s effect in GY, banishing it to Special Summon Beckoned from GY to the Monster Zone Almiraj points to. Synchro Ib and Beckoned into Lightstorm Dragon. Ib triggers in GY to Special Summon any World Chalice monster from Deck or GY, so bring back World Chalice from GY. Activate Monstrosity targeting Lightstorm to Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and Deus-X Krawler from Deck. Xyz Deus-X and Lightstorm into Mereologic Aggregator who sends Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY on Xyz Summon. Herald triggers in GY to search for Prediction Princess Tarotrei. Aggregator activates its other effect targeting Herald in GY, detaching 1, and attaching Herald back from GY. Link Aggregator and Almiraj into Lib the World Key Blademaster. Herald triggers after being sent to GY again to search for Underworld Ritual of Prediction. Lib activates to set World Legacy Pawns from Deck. Then, Link Lib and World Chalice into S:P Little Knight. Activate Underworld Ritual to Ritual Summon Tarotrei by tributing Bibliomuse. Bibliomuse triggers in GY off of being tributed and Special Summons herself back from GY face-down. Activate Tarotrei to flip Bibliomuse face-up. Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect searches for Prediction Princess Tarotreith and another Underworld Ritual. Activate Underworld Ritual tributing Bibliomuse to Ritual Summon Tarotreith face-down. During the End Phase, Tarotrei Special Summons Deus-X back from GY face-down. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, you can banish Underworld Ritual from GY to Special Summon a Bibliomuse from Deck face-down and then Tarotrei can flip Tarotreith face-up. Tarotreith’s Flip Effect Special Summons Summoner of Illusions from Deck and then its other effect can flip up both Bibliomuse and Deus-X. To go over what we now have, we have S:P Little Knight, Bibliomuse searches follow-up in another Tarotrei and another Underworld Ritual while also giving your Ritual Monsters targeting and destruction protection, Deus-X negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field, and then you have Pawns set which can flip up Summoner of Illusions who tributes another monster to Special Summon Odd-Eyes Vortex Dragon since we have a Pendulum Monster (Prima Materiactor) in our Extra Deck face-up. Vortex Dragon can then target a face-up Attack Position monster your opponent controls and bounce it and it can also Quick Effect negate an activated Spell/Trap card or monster effect by shuffling the face-up Prima Materiactor in our Extra Deck back into the Deck and destroy that card. 

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Pot of the Forbidden which has a Flip Effect that lets you choose between Drawing 2 cards, returning all Spell/Traps on the field to the hand, destroying all monsters your opponent controls, or looking at your opponent's hand and shuffling a card from it back into the Deck. 1 Summoner of Illusions whose Flip Effect is a mandatory effect activation when it is flipped face-up which tributes another monster you control to Special Summon a Fusion Monster from your Extra Deck, but that monster is destroyed during the End Phase of the turn. 1 Prima Materiactor. So why are we playing this? Well, we need a Normal Monster with 0 ATK to search off of Piri Reis Map since we are playing it to search for World Legacy - “World Chalice”, so in the case that we do open both a World Chalice and a Map, we still have full combo. And because that Normal Monster needs to be Normal Summonable (i.e. Level 4 or lower), our options are between Soul Tiger, Gem-Knight Sapphire, Doll Monster Bear-Bear, Doll Monster Miss Mädchen, Dipity, Igknight Squire, Prima Materiactor, Soitsu, Guardragon Justicia, Melffy Rabby, Metalfoes Steelen, Crowned by the World Chalice, the 3 Ojama brothers (Green, Yellow, and Black), White Duston, Sunseed Genius Loci, Thousand-Eyes Idol, and if you live in the OCG, Space Omajinai Usagi. You can play ANY of these monsters in this slot (I personally like Soitsu), but since we are playing Summoner of Illusions, we can play a Pendulum Normal Monster in order to be able to use both effects of Odd-Eyes Vortex Dragon, specifically its negate which requires you to shuffle a face-up Pendulum Monster in your Extra Deck back into the Deck as part of its effect. So, that leaves you with Prima Materiactor, Igknight Squire, and Metalfoes Steelen, so take your pick. 2 Beckoned by the World Chalice. Why this monster of all the World Chalice vanilla monsters? Basically, we need to access World Chalice Guardragon off of World Chalice’s GY effect and we are then putting it into the GY by using it as Synchro Material for Ib the World Chalice Justiciar. Beckoned can be treated as a Tuner when Synchro Summoning Ib and it’s a Level 4, so 4 plus 1 equals 5. Furthermore, World Chalice Guardragon then brings back Beckoned from GY and whaddya know, Ib is a Level 5 Tuner and Beckoned is a Level 4, so that gives you a Level 9 Synchro Monster to target with Monstrosity. 3 World Legacy - “World Chalice” which if it is Normal Summoned/Set and leaves the field, it can Special Summon 2 World Chalice monsters from your Deck except for World Chalice. You can also banish it from GY except the turn it was sent there to search for a World Legacy card from Deck. I wish we could use this card to search for a second Monstrosity for more Rank 9 potential on a following turn, but we aren’t playing enough Level 9’s to make this feasible. World Chalice has another effect which if a monster(s) is Special Summoned from the Extra Deck, you can tribute it to send that monster(s) to the GY. You could use this effect if you bring back World Chalice from GY with Ib and keep it around, but that’s probably not what you are usually going to be going for. 1 World Chalice Guardragon which can banish itself from Gy and target a Normal Monster in your GY to Special Summon that monster in Defense Position to Linkpoint. This card is a brick, so if you draw it, just cry I guess. Finally, 3 Mulcharmy Fuwalos, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, and 3 Droll & Lock Bird. 

For Spell/Traps: 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 1 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. 3 Primite Roar which you pay 2000 LP and declare a Normal Monster Card’s name and then Normal Monsters with that name and Primite monsters you control cannot be destroyed by battle until the end of your opponent’s turn and then if you control no monsters, you can Special Summon a Normal Monster with the declared name from your Deck in Defense Position. Also, if your opponent Normal Summons a monster, you can banish this card from your GY and target a Normal Monster you control or in your GY to banish a monster on field with less ATK on that monster. Our target for this effect is Beckoned by the World Chalice, and 1800 ATK covers a lot of ground. 2 Primite Lordly Lode which just is here to search for Primite Roar on activation. 3 Piri Reis Map, which at the start of your Main Phase 1 allows you to add a monster with 0 ATK from your Deck to your hand, halving your Life Points, but preventing you from activating the activated monster’s effects or the effects of cards with the same name until the end of the next turn until your Normal Summon that monster or a card with its name. This searches for World Legacy - “World Chalice” and the Prima Materiactor we are playing. 3 Infinite Impermanence and 1 World Legacy Pawns which can target a face-down monster you control can change it to face-up Attack or Defense Position. 

Extra Deck: 1 Flowering Etoile the Melodious Magnificat. As a Summoner of Illusions target, it can Quick Effect banish any number of Melodious monsters you control until the End Phase (i.e. just itself) and then you can return the same number of face-up cards your opponent controls to the hand (i.e. just one). Flowering Etoile is one of the few Fusion Monsters that can bypass Summoner of Illusions’s End Phase destruction clause since she effectively dodges it as she banishes herself until the End Phase. I am not sure what exact ruling explains this, but testing it on multiple simulators, this does seem to be the case. 1 Odd-Eyes Vortex Dragon as our other SoI target in the Extra Deck. On Special Summon, it can target and bounce a face-up Attack Position monster your opponent controls. And if your opponent activates a Spell/Trap Card or another monster’s effect, it can Quick Effect shuffle a face-up Pendulum Monster in your Extra Deck into the Deck to negate and destroy that card. 1 Lightstorm Dragon which is pretty useful in this Deck as on Special Summon, you can target Spell/Traps on the field up to the number of Normal Monsters in your GY +1 and destroy them. Note that this is on Special Summon, so if you bring it back with like Nine-Lives Cat or World Legacy Succession (both of which you can choose to play), it can pop some backrow for you. Otherwise, it is the Level 9 Synchro that we are playing to target with Monstrosity. 1 Ib the World Chalice Justiciar who can treat a World Chalice Normal Monster as a Tuner for her Synchro Summon and on Synchro Summon, she searches a World Legacy card from Deck. Also, if she’s Synchro Summoned and sent from field to GY, she can Special Summon a World Chalice monster from your Deck or GY other than herself. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from your Deck to your hand if it is sent to the GY. 2 Mereologic Aggregator, 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows, and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Underworld Goddess of the Closed World. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 Lib the World Key Blademaster who requires you to have a World Legacy card in GY to be able to be Link Summoned and she can set a World Legacy card from your Deck with it being unable to be activated within the same turn if you don’t have a World Legacy monster in GY. Also, if she is used as Link Material and sent to GY after being Link Summoned, she can spin a card on field into the Deck. 1 Imduk the World Chalice Dragon who requires a Normal Monster other than a Token as Link Material and gives an additional Normal Summon of a World Chalice monster once per turn. Finally, 1 Salamangreat Almiraj to Link off World Chalice. 

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Mulcharmy Purulia, 2 Triple Tactics Thrust, 1 Triple Tactics Talent, 2 Lightning Storm, 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: Yubel deck combined with friendsmith controls the field
deck_description: Yubel deck combined with friendsmith controls the field

Engines are not meant to bridge into one another; how you play determines on your opener. Both are strong going-first and going-second, and opening a mix of K9 and Mitsurugi allows for extremely disruption-resistant board-breaking via Zeus/Murakumo/Werewolf, or ending on extremely threatening game states like two R5s on-field + Murakumo + S:P + set Prayers/Release + Izuna in hand/Lupis in rotation + Wousu and Mitsu in-hand game 1.

Since Mitsurugi is worse going first, Zombie Vampire is played to sometimes allow bridging into K9 engine by milling names if full Mitsu engine is opened. Noroi is played as few hands ever necessitate an NS, meaning you can sometimes Appointer your opponent turn 1 for free by sending Case/itself. Urubonus might be better to play than 2nd Ritual, but I have found 2nd Ritual to come up more when playing 2 Jokul.

The set Detonate to the Top Speed is a Selection Pack, released on August 4, 2025. MASTER DUEL - HOW TO PLAY! COMBO RYZEAL DECK WITH BIG JAWS - POWER OF THE SEA. Hopefully this video will help everyone build and play decks more easily. Below is the deck profile for everyone to refer to. Subsrice F2P WGamer: https://www.youtube.com/c/F2PWGamer

Synchro Summon "Junk Speeder" and active "Junk Speeder"'s effect: Special Summon 1 level 3 Synchron monster from deck. (Alternative(ly) if "Revolution Synchron" on the hand Synchro Summon "Power Tool Dragon" using "Revolution Synchron" and level 4 monster on the field then Special Summon "Revolution Synchron" as Level 1 monster from the GY). 

 

Synchro Summon "Centur-Ion Primera Primus" either using "Junk Speeder" and level 3 Synchron Monster or "Power Tool Dragon" and level 1 tuner monster as Synchro Materials.

 

Activate "Centur-Ion Primera Primus"'s effect when Synchro Summoned: add "Emblema Oath" Spell Card from your Deck to your hand. 

 

Activate "Emblema Oath"'s effect: place "Centur-Ion Gargoyle II" from your Deck into your Spell & Trap Zone as a face-up Continuous Trap. 

 

Activate "Centur-Ion Gargoyle II"'s effect to Special Summon itself, then reduce its Level by 4. 

 

Synchro Summon "Centur-Ion Auxila" using "Centur-Ion Primera Primus" and "Centur-Ion Gargoyle II" as Synchro Materials. 

 

Activate "Centur-Ion Auxila"'s effect when Special Summoned: add "Stand Up Centur-Ion!" Field Spell Card from your Deck to your hand. 

 

Activate "Centur-Ion Gargoyle II"'s effect: if it was sent to the GY as Synchro Material, add it to your hand. 

 

Activate "Stand Up Centur-Ion!": send "Centur-Ion Gargoyle II" from your hand to the GY to place "Centur-Ion Trudea" from your Deck into your Spell & Trap Zone as a face-up Continuous Trap. 

 

Activate "Centur-Ion Trudea"'s effect to Special Summon itself. 

 

Activate "Centur-Ion Trudea" again: place itself and "Centur-Ion Primera" from your hand or Deck into your Spell & Trap Zones as face-up Continuous Traps. 

 

Activate "Centur-Ion Primera"'s effect to Special Summon itself. When Special Summoned, activate its effect to add "Wake Up Centur-Ion!" Quick-Play Spell from your Deck to your hand. 

 

Activate "Wake Up Centur-Ion!": declare Level 8, Special Summon 1 "Centur-Ion Token", then banish "Wake Up Centur-Ion!" from your GY to send "Centur-Ion Phalanx" from your Deck to the GY. 

 

Synchro Summon "Crimson Dragon" using "Centur-Ion Primera" and the "Centur-Ion Token" as Synchro Materials. 

 

Banish "Centur-Ion Phalanx" from your GY to target "Centur-Ion Primera Primus" in your GY; Special Summon "Centur-Ion Primera Primus" in Defense Position. 

 

Activate "Crimson Dragon"'s effect: target "Centur-Ion Auxila", return "Crimson Dragon" to the Extra Deck, then Synchro Summon "Cosmic Blazar Dragon" from the Extra Deck. 

 

End Turn. During the End Phase, activate "Centur-Ion Auxila"'s effect to place "Centur-Ion Gargoyle II", which is in your GY, into your Spell & Trap Zone as a face-up Continuous Trap. 

 

During Your Opponent’s Main Phase: 

 

Activate "Centur-Ion Gargoyle II"’s effect to Special Summon it and reduce its Level to 4. 

 

Trigger "Stand Up Centur-Ion!"’s effect: if a monster(s) is Special Summoned, immediately after this effect resolves, Synchro Summon 1 Synchro Monster. 

 

Use this to Synchro Summon "Crimson Dragon" using "Centur-Ion Primera Primus" and "Centur-Ion Gargoyle II" as Synchro Materials. 

 

Activate "Centur-Ion Gargoyle II"’s effect: if sent to the GY as Synchro Material, add it to your hand. 

 

Activate "Crimson Dragon"’s effect: target "Cosmic Blazar Dragon", return "Crimson Dragon" to the Extra Deck, then Synchro Summon either "Crystal Clear Wing Over Synchro Dragon" or "Stardust Sifr Divine Dragon" (depend on which deck the opponent use). 

 

During the End Phase, activate "Centur-Ion Auxila"’s effect to place "Centur-Ion Primera", which is in your GY, into your Spell & Trap Zone as a face-up Continuous Trap. 

 

Next Turn: 

 

Activate "Centur-Ion Primera"’s effect to Special Summon itself. 

 

Activate "Centur-Ion Gargoyle II" from your hand: send the face-up Continuous Trap "Centur-Ion Trudea" in your Spell & Trap Zone to the GY; Special Summon "Centur-Ion Gargoyle II" from your hand. 

 

Synchro Summon "Crimson Dragon" using "Centur-Ion Primera" and "Centur-Ion Gargoyle II" as Synchro Materials. 

 

(Optional) Activate "Centur-Ion Gargoyle II"’s effect: if sent to the GY as Synchro Material, add it to your hand. 

 

Activate "Crimson Dragon"’s effect: target "Cosmic Blazar Dragon", return "Crimson Dragon" to the Extra Deck, then Synchro Summon whichever monster you did not summon previously — "Crystal Clear Wing Over Synchro Dragon" or "Stardust Sifr Divine Dragon". 

 

✅ Final Board (if executed correctly): 

 

• Stardust Sifr Divine Dragon 

 

• Centur-Ion Auxila 

 

• Crystal Clear Wing Over Synchro Dragon 

 

• Cosmic Blazar Dragon 

 

• Stand Up Centur-Ion! (Field Spell)

deck_excerpt: This deck is held together by popsicle sticks and miracles... At least that's what is says in arc pendulum's flavour text.
deck_description:
*Replace "Regenesis Code" with "Regenesis" normal spell that searches Regenesis monsters. Couldn't find it for some reason.*

 

The deck aims to utilize the kashtira engine and the regenesis monsters to set up free bodies to facilitate the main pendulum combo, as well as set up layered forms of interaction in the endboard. In theory, both these engine can also serve as handtrap bait in Game 1 and make your opponent think you are playing a "good" deck. Regenesis archfiend search sage can also act to insulate "Beyond the pendulum" from handtraps or archfiend can grab Regenesis birth, if archfiend is needed as material to make "beyond the pendulum". 

Playing the kashtira package with birth and unicorn gives the deck some additonal follow up, something pendulum is notorious for lacking. There are some anti-synergies with the kashtira monsters and dragon shrine, but the free bodies, endboard interactions, and board breaking capabilites of the kashtira monsters are worth that risk. Wraitsoth also boosts your monsters by about 300-500 ATK due to the variety of attributes this deck is ends on.

Both the kashtira and regenesis engines are made of level 7 monsters (with the exception of archfiend), which aid in making absolute dragon and the subsequent summoning of vortex dragon

This deck has about 16 ways to get gate magician and 10 ways to get darkwurm, but the main pendulum core often lacks a good way to get to a second body on board, which has been partly resolved by playing the two other engines. Beyond the pendulum will most often be grabbing lightwurm to faciliate pendulum summons or Arc pendulum to get the brick out of the deck and make absolute dragon, if lightwurm is already in hand.

The deck often dies to about 2 handtraps on average, depending on how many engines are in the opening hand, and it instantly dies to "Droll & lock bird".

Good luck to anyone who decides to play this deck.
